<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-495-937  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 495 937.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 8 1990 v4 n36 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EDMICS takes lead in CALS standards. (Engineering Data ManagementInformation and Control Systems) (Computer-Aided Acquisition andLogistics Support Program)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richardson, Jennifer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The completion of a major Computer-Aided Acquisition and LogisticsSupport (CALS)-compliant project test is driving some CALSstandards despite the fact that the Department of Defense and theNational Institute of Standards and Technology have yet to fullydefine those standards.andP;  The project, called EDMICS, wasundertaken by the Navy to store and retrieve engineering data fromeight major repositories.andP;  CALS, a program initiated in 1984 toautomate the design, purchase and maintenance of weapons, has beenprogressing slowly, and now the Navy has come under criticism forits piece-meal approach to developing EDMICS.andP;  Some of the maincomplaints are that not all of the electronic data interchangestandards or optical disk standards have been selected and manystandards are being implemented as the systems are developed.andP;  Thefinal EDMICS testing stage began the first week of Oct 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardizationWeapons IndustryInformation Storage and RetrievalAutomationUnited States. Department of Defense.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>